{{Infobox royalty |name = Fujiwara no Genshi |succession = [[Japanese empresses|Empress consort of Japan]] |reign = 1037–1039 |consort = yes |spouse = [[Emperor Go-Suzaku]] |issue = {{plainlist| * Princess Yūshi * Princess Baishi }} |house = [[Imperial House of Japan|Yamato]] |father = Prince Atsuyasu |mother = |birth_date = August 24, 1016 |birth_place = |death_date = {{death date and age|1039|9|19|1016|8|24}} |death_place = |burial_date = |burial_place = |}}
{{Nihongo|'''Fujiwara no Genshi'''|藤原 嫄子||August 24, 1016 – September 19, 1039}}, born {{Nihongo|'''Princess Genshi'''|嫄子女王}}, was an Empress consort of middle-[[Heian period]] Japan. She was an empress consort (''[[chūgū]]'') of [[Emperor Go-Suzaku]] of Japan.
She was the adopted daughter of [[Fujiwara no Yorimichi]] and biological daughter of {{Nihongo|Imperial Prince Atsuyasu|敦康親王}}.
== Life == Genshi's father Atsuyasu died in 1018. Her mother was the younger sister of [[Fujiwara no Yorimichi]]'s official wife, Princess Takahime, and so the daughterless Yorimichi adopted her. In 1036, she acted as a substitute court lady in the purification ceremony at [[Emperor Go-Suzaku]]'s first ''niiname-sai'' harvest festival. The next year, she entered his court as a court lady, and received the [[Ritsuryō#Establishment of court rank|rank]] of {{Nihongo||正四位下|shō shi-i no ge}}. Two months later she was made ''chūgū'', displacing the existing empress consort [[Princess Teishi]] to ''[[Japanese empresses|kōgō]]'' and souring relations between Teishi and Yorimichi. Favored by the Emperor, Genshi bore him two girls, but died in childbirth at the age of 24 without giving birth to a prince.
According to the {{Nihongo|records of [[Ise Shrine]]|太神宮諸雑事記|daijingū shozō-kiji}}, when Genshi was bathing ten days after giving birth, there was a great storm. Amidst the lightning and thunder and heavy rain, Genshi died on the spot. At the time, there was a rumor that the Fujiwara family god of [[Kasuga-taisha]] was angered that Genshi had been made Empress through adoption into the [[Fujiwara clan]], despite blood ties to the [[Minamoto clan]].
== Issue ==
* Imperial Princess ''Yūshi''/Sukeko (祐子内親王) (1038–1105) - (Sanpon-Jusangū, 三品准三宮) * Imperial Princess ''Baishi'' (禖子内親王) (Rokujō Saiin, 六条斎院) (1039–1096) - [[Saiin (Priestess)|Saiin]] at [[Kamo Shrine]] 1046–1058
