* {{cite journal | display-authors = 8| author = Temel JS| author2 = Greer JA| author3 = Muzikansky A| author4 = Gallagher ER| author5 = Admane S| author6 = Jackson VA| author7 = Dahlin CM| author8 = Blinderman CD| author9 = Jacobsen J| author10 = Pirl WF| author11 = Billings JA| author12 = Lynch TJ | title = Early Palliative Care for Patients with Metastatic Non–Small-Cell Lung Cancer | journal = New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 363 | issue = 8 | pages = 733–742 | date = 2010 | pmid = 20818875 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa1000678 }}</ref> Palliative care increases comfort by lessening pain, controlling symptoms, and lessening stress for the patient and family, and should not be delayed when it is indicated.<ref name="AAHPMfive"/> Evidence shows that end-of-life communication interventions decrease utilization (such as length of stay), particularly in the intensive care unit setting,<ref>{{cite journal | display-authors = 8| author = Fawole OA| author2 =  Dy SM| author3 = Wilson RF| author4 = Lau BD| author5 = Martinez KA| author6 = Apostol CC| author7 = Vollenweider D| author8 = Bass EB| author9 = Aslakson RA | title = A systematic review of communication quality improvement interventions for patients with advanced and serious illness | journal = J Gen Intern Med
| volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 570–7 | date = 2013 | pmid = 23099799 | doi = 10.1007/s11606-012-2204-4 | pmc=3599019}}</ref> and that palliative care interventions (mostly in the outpatient setting) are effective for improving patient and caregiver perceptions of care.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Dy SM| author2 = Apostol C| author3 = Martinez KA| author4 = Aslakson RA | title = Continuity, coordination, and transitions of care for patients with serious and advanced illness: a systematic review of interventions | journal = J Palliat Med | volume = 16 | issue = 4| pages = 436–45 | date = 2013 | doi =10.1089/jpm.2012.0317 | pmid = 23488450}}</ref>

Palliative care is not reserved for people in [[end-of-life care]] and can improve [[quality of life]], decrease depressive symptoms, and increase survival time.<ref name="AAHPMfive"/> If palliative care is indicated for a person in an [[emergency department]], then that care should begin in the emergency department immediately and with referral to additional palliative care services.<ref name="ACEPfive">{{Citation |author1 = American College of Emergency Physicians |author1-link = American College of Emergency Physicians |title = Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher = American College of Emergency Physicians |work = [[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |url = http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-college-of-emergency-physicians/ |accessdate = January 24, 2014}}, which cites:
* {{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/medical_examiner/2010/08/we_cant_save_you.html |title=How to tell emergency room patients that they're dying |first=Joanne  |last=Kenen |work=slate.com |date=4 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}
* {{cite journal|last1=Quest|first1=Tammie E.|last2=Marco|first2=Catherine A.|last3=Derse|first3=Arthur R.|title=Hospice and Palliative Medicine: New Subspecialty, New Opportunities|journal=Annals of Emergency Medicine|volume=54|issue=1|date=2009|pages=94–102|issn=0196-0644|doi=10.1016/j.annemergmed.2008.11.019|pmid=19185393}}</ref> Emergency care physicians often are the first medical professionals to open the discussion about palliative care and hospice services with people needing care and their families.<ref name="ACEPfive"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=A. K.|last2=McCarthy|first2=E.|last3=Weber|first3=E.|last4=Cenzer|first4=I. S.|last5=Boscardin|first5=J.|last6=Fisher|first6=J.|last7=Covinsky|first7=K.|title=Half Of Older Americans Seen In Emergency Department In Last Month Of Life; Most Admitted To Hospital, And Many Die There|journal=Health Affairs|volume=31|issue=6|date=2012|pages=1277–1285|issn=0278-2715|doi=10.1377/hlthaff.2011.0922|pmid=22665840|pmc=3736978}}</ref>

In some cases, [[Specialty (medicine)|medical specialty]] [[professional organizations]] recommend that sick people and physicians respond to an illness only with palliative care and not with a therapy directed at the disease. The following items are indications named by the [[American Society of Clinical Oncology]] as characteristics of a person who should receive palliative care but not any cancer-directed therapy.<ref name="ASCOfive">{{Citation |author1 = American Society of Clinical Oncology |author1-link = American Society of Clinical Oncology |title = Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher = [[American Society of Clinical Oncology]] |work = Choosing Wisely: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |url = http://choosingwisely.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/5things_12_factsheet_Amer_Soc_Clin_Onc.pdf |accessdate = August 14, 2012 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120731073425/http://choosingwisely.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/5things_12_factsheet_Amer_Soc_Clin_Onc.pdf |archivedate = July 31, 2012 |df =  }}</ref><ref>
